+The '''Christianization of Kievan Rus'''' was a long and complicated process that took place in several stages.{{sfn|Katchanovski|Kohut|Nesebio|Yurkevich|2013|p=74–75}} In 867, [[Photios I of Constantinople|Patriarch Photius]] of Constantinople told other Christian patriarchs that the [[Rus' people]] were converting enthusiastically, but his efforts seem to have entailed no lasting consequences, since the ''[[Primary Chronicle]]'' and other Slavonic sources describe the tenth-century Rus' as still firmly entrenched in [[Slavic paganism]]. The traditional view, as recorded in the ''Primary Chronicle'', is that the definitive Christianization of Kievan Rus' dates happened {{circa}} 988 (the year is disputed<ref>Oleg Rapov, ''Russkaya tserkov v IX&ndash;pervoy treti XII veka'' (''The Russian Church from the 9th to the First 3rd of the 12th Century''). Moscow, 1988.</ref>), when [[Vladimir the Great|Vladimir/Volodymyr the Great]] was baptized in [[Chersonesus]] (''Korsun'') and proceeded to baptize his family and people in [[Kyiv|Kiev]]. The latter events are traditionally referred to as '''baptism of Rus' ''' ({{lang-ru|Крещение Руси}}; {{lang-ua|Хрещення Русі}}) in Ukrainian and Russian literature.

 == Antiquity ==
-Although sometimes solely attributed to Vladimir/Volodymyr, the Christianisation of Kyivan Rus' was a long and complicated process that began before the state's formation.{{sfn|Katchanovski|Kohut|Nesebio|Yurkevich|2013|p=74}} As early as the 1st century CE, [[Greek colonisation|Greeks in the Black Sea Colonies]] converted to Christianity, although most of these lands never became part of Kyivan Rus'.{{sfn|Katchanovski|Kohut|Nesebio|Yurkevich|2013|p=74}} The ''[[Primary Chronicle]]'' records the legend of [[Andrew the Apostle]]'s mission to these coastal settlements, as well as blessing the site of present-day Kyiv.{{sfn|Katchanovski|Kohut|Nesebio|Yurkevich|2013|p=74}} Andrew supposedly visited [[Chersonesus Taurica]] in [[Crimea]], where he converted several thousand men to the new faith, and on his way north along the Dnipro reached the future locations of Kyiv and [[Veliky Novgorod]].{{says who?|date=October 2022}} The legendary account in the ''Primary Chronicle'' tells that Andrew was amused by the Slavic customs of washing in a hot steam bath, [[banya (sauna)|banya]], on his way.{{says who?|date=October 2022}} The [[Goths]] migrated to through the region in the 3rd century, adopting [[Arian Christianity]] in the 4th century, leaving behind 4th- and 5th-century churches excavated in Crimea (which was outside of Kyivan control, except for [[Tmutarakan]]), although the [[Huns|Hunnic]] invasion of the 370s halted Christianisation for several centuries.{{sfn|Katchanovski|Kohut|Nesebio|Yurkevich|2013|p=74}}
