-The '''Christianization of Kievan Rus'''' was a long and complicated process that took place in several stages.{{sfn|Katchanovski|Kohut|Nesebio|Yurkevich|2013|p=74–75}} In 867, [[Photios I of Constantinople|Patriarch Photius]] of Constantinople told other Christian patriarchs that the [[Rus' people]] were converting enthusiastically, but his efforts seem to have entailed no lasting consequences, since the ''[[Primary Chronicle]]'' and other Slavonic sources describe the tenth-century Rus' as still firmly entrenched in [[Slavic paganism]]. The traditional view, as recorded in the ''Primary Chronicle'', is that the definitive Christianization of Kievan Rus' dates happened {{circa}} 988 (the year is disputed<ref>Oleg Rapov, ''Russkaya tserkov v IX&ndash;pervoy treti XII veka'' (''The Russian Church from the 9th to the First 3rd of the 12th Century''). Moscow, 1988.</ref>), when [[Vladimir the Great|Vladimir/Volodymyr the Great]] was baptized in [[Chersonesus]] (''Korsun'') and proceeded to baptize his family and people in [[Kyiv|Kiev]]. The latter events are traditionally referred to as '''baptism of Rus' ''' ({{lang-ru|Крещение Руси}}; {{lang-ua|Хрещення Русі}}) in Ukrainian and Russian literature.
+The '''Christianization of Kievan Rus'''' was a long and complicated process that took place in several stages.{{sfn|Katchanovski|Kohut|Nesebio|Yurkevich|2013|p=74–75}} In 867, [[Photios I of Constantinople|Patriarch Photius]] of Constantinople told other Christian patriarchs that the [[Rus' people]] were converting enthusiastically, but his efforts seem to have entailed no lasting consequences, since the ''[[Primary Chronicle]]'' and other Slavonic sources describe the tenth-century Rus' as still firmly entrenched in [[Slavic paganism]]. The traditional view, as recorded in the ''Primary Chronicle'', is that the definitive Christianization of Kievan Rus' dates happened {{circa}} 988 (the year is disputed<ref>Oleg Rapov, ''Russkaya tserkov v IX&ndash;pervoy treti XII veka'' (''The Russian Church from the 9th to the First 3rd of the 12th Century''). Moscow, 1988.</ref>), when [[Vladimir the Great|Vladimir the Great]] was baptized in [[Chersonesus]] (''Korsun'') and proceeded to baptize his family and people in [[Kiev]]. The latter events are traditionally referred to as '''baptism of Rus' ''' ({{lang-ru|Крещение Руси}}; {{lang-ua|Хрещення Русі}}) in Ukrainian and Russian literature.

 == Antiquity ==
-Although sometimes solely attributed to Vladimir/Volodymyr, the Christianisation of Kievan Rus' was a long and complicated process that began before the state's formation.{{sfn|Katchanovski|Kohut|Nesebio|Yurkevich|2013|p=74}} As early as the 1st century CE, [[Greek colonisation|Greeks in the Black Sea Colonies]] converted to Christianity, although most of these lands never became part of Kyivan Rus'.{{sfn|Katchanovski|Kohut|Nesebio|Yurkevich|2013|p=74}} The ''[[Primary Chronicle]]'' records the legend of [[Andrew the Apostle]]'s mission to these coastal settlements, as well as blessing the site of present-day Kyiv.{{sfn|Katchanovski|Kohut|Nesebio|Yurkevich|2013|p=74}} Andrew supposedly visited [[Chersonesus Taurica]] in [[Crimea]], where he converted several thousand men to the new faith, and on his way north along the Dnipro reached the future locations of Kyiv.{{says who?|date=October 2022}} The legendary account in the ''Primary Chronicle'' tells that Andrew was amused by the Slavic customs of washing in a hot steam bath, [[banya (sauna)|banya]], on his way.{{says who?|date=October 2022}} The [[Goths]] migrated to through the region in the 3rd century, adopting [[Arian Christianity]] in the 4th century, leaving behind 4th- and 5th-century churches excavated in Crimea (which was outside of Kyivan control, except for [[Tmutarakan]]), although the [[Huns|Hunnic]] invasion of the 370s halted Christianisation for several centuries.{{sfn|Katchanovski|Kohut|Nesebio|Yurkevich|2013|p=74}}
+Although sometimes solely attributed to Vladimir/Volodymyr, the Christianisation of Kievan Rus' was a long and complicated process that began before the state's formation.{{sfn|Katchanovski|Kohut|Nesebio|Yurkevich|2013|p=74}} As early as the 1st century CE, [[Greek colonisation|Greeks in the Black Sea Colonies]] converted to Christianity, although most of these lands never became part of Kievan Rus'.{{sfn|Katchanovski|Kohut|Nesebio|Yurkevich|2013|p=74}} The ''[[Primary Chronicle]]'' records the legend of [[Andrew the Apostle]]'s mission to these coastal settlements, as well as blessing the site of present-day Kiev.{{sfn|Katchanovski|Kohut|Nesebio|Yurkevich|2013|p=74}} Andrew supposedly visited [[Chersonesus Taurica]] in [[Crimea]], where he converted several thousand men to the new faith, and on his way north along the Dnepr reached the future locations of Kiev.{{says who?|date=October 2022}} The legendary account in the ''Primary Chronicle'' tells that Andrew was amused by the Slavic customs of washing in a hot steam bath, [[banya (sauna)|banya]], on his way.{{says who?|date=October 2022}} The [[Goths]] migrated to through the region in the 3rd century, adopting [[Arian Christianity]] in the 4th century, leaving behind 4th- and 5th-century churches excavated in Crimea (which was outside of Kievan control, except for [[Tmutarakan]]), although the [[Huns|Hunnic]] invasion of the 370s halted Christianisation for several centuries.{{sfn|Katchanovski|Kohut|Nesebio|Yurkevich|2013|p=74}}

 == Ninth century ==
 Some of the earliest Kievan princes and princesses such as [[Askold and Dir]] and [[Olga of Kiev|Olha of Kiev]] reportedly converted to Christianity, but [[Oleg the Wise]], [[Igor of Kiev]] and [[Sviatoslav I|Svyatoslav]] remained pagans.{{sfn|Katchanovski|Kohut|Nesebio|Yurkevich|2013|p=74–75}} According to some sources and historians, there was an attempt in the 9th century to Christianise Kievan Rus'. The most authoritative source for this purported first conversion attempt is an [[encyclical]] letter of [[Photios I of Constantinople|Patriarch Photius]] of [[Constantinople]], datable to early 867. Referencing the [[Rus'-Byzantine War (860)|Rus'-Byzantine War of 860]], Photius informs the Oriental [[patriarchate|patriarchs]] and bishops that, after the [[First Bulgarian Empire|Bulgarians]] [[Christianization of Bulgaria|turned to Christ]] in 864,<ref>History of the Bulgarians from Antiquity to the 16th Century by Georgi Bakalov (2003) {{ISBN|954-528-289-4}}</ref> the Rus' followed suit so zealously that he found it prudent to send to their land a [[bishop]].<ref>Photii Patriarchae Constantinopolitani Epistulae et Amphilochia. Ed. B. Laourdas, L.G. Westerinck. T.1. Leipzig, 1983. P. 49.</ref>
@@ -32,13 +32,13 @@
 Sviatoslav's successor, [[Yaropolk I]] (r. 972–980), seems to have had a more conciliatory attitude towards Christianity. Late medieval sources even claim that Yaropolk exchanged ambassadors with the Pope. The ''Chronicon'' of [[Adémar de Chabannes]] and the life of [[St. Romuald]] (by [[Pietro Damiani]]) actually document the mission of St. [[Bruno of Querfurt]] to the land of Rus', where he succeeded in converting to Christianity a local king (one of three brothers who ruled the land). [[Alexander Nazarenko]] suggests that Yaropolk went through some preliminary rites of baptism, but was murdered at the behest of his pagan half-brother Vladimir (whose own rights to the throne were questionable) before his conversion was formalized. Following this theory, any information on Yaropolk's baptism according to the [[Latin liturgical rites|Latin form]] would be suppressed by the later Eastern Orthodox chroniclers, zealous to keep Vladimir's image of the Rus Apostle untarnished for succeeding generations.<ref>[[Alexander Nazarenko]]. ''Древняя Русь на международных путях''. Moscow, 2001. {{ISBN|5-7859-0085-8}}.</ref>

