-The '''Christianization of Kievan Rus'''' was a long and complicated process that took place in several stages.{{sfn|Katchanovski|Kohut|Nesebio|Yurkevich|2013|p=74–75}} In 867, [[Photios I of Constantinople|Patriarch Photius]] of Constantinople told other Christian patriarchs that the [[Rus' people]] were converting enthusiastically, but his efforts seem to have entailed no lasting consequences, since the ''[[Russian Primary Chronicle]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.swarthmore.edu/muslim-russia/rusian-primary-chronicle |title=The Rusian Primary Chronicle |language=en |access-date=2023-11-28 |publisher=Swarthmore}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://philpapers.org/rec/DVOTRP |title=The Russian primary chronicle and the Vlachs of Eastern Europe |language=en |access-date=2023-11-28 |publisher=philpapers.org}}</ref> and other Slavonic sources describe the tenth-century Rus' as still firmly entrenched in [[Slavic paganism]]. The traditional view, as recorded in the ''Russian Primary Chronicle'',<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.swarthmore.edu/muslim-russia/rusian-primary-chronicle |title=The Rusian Primary Chronicle |language=en |access-date=2023-11-28 |publisher=Swarthmore}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://philpapers.org/rec/DVOTRP |title=The Russian primary chronicle and the Vlachs of Eastern Europe |language=en |access-date=2023-11-28 |publisher=philpapers.org}}</ref> is that the definitive Christianization of Kievan Rus' dates happened {{circa}} 988<ref>{{cite web |url=https://human.libretexts.org/Courses/Lumen_Learning/Book%3A_Early_World_Civilizations_(Lumen)/Ch._08_The_Development_of_Russia/09.2%3A_Vladimir_I_and_Christianization |title=Vladimir I and Christianization |language=en |access-date=2023-11-28 |publisher=libretexts}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.advantour.com/russia/history/christianization-of-kievan-rus.htm |title=Christianization of Russia |language=en |access-date=2023-11-28 |publisher=advantour}}</ref> (the year is disputed<ref>Oleg Rapov, ''Russkaya tserkov v IX&ndash;pervoy treti XII veka'' (''The Russian Church from the 9th to the First 3rd of the 12th Century''). Moscow, 1988.</ref>), when [[Vladimir the Great]] was baptized in [[Chersonesus]] (''Korsun'') and proceeded to baptize his family and people in [[Kiev]]. The latter events are traditionally referred to as '''baptism of Rus' ''' ({{lang-ru|Крещение Руси}}; {{lang-uk|Хрещення Русі}}; {{lang-be|Вадохрышча Русі}}) in Russian, Ukrainian and Belarusian literature.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.belapc.org/litaratura/apanas-martas-belarus-v-istoriceskoj-cerkovnoj-i-gosudarstvennoj-zizni/cast-vtoraa-cerkovnaa---glava-i-hristianstvo-v-belarusi |title=ЧАСТЬ ВТОРАЯ, ЦЕРКОВНАЯ - ГЛАВА I. ХРИСТИАНСТВО В БЕЛАРУСИ |language=ru |access-date=2023-11-28 |publisher=belapc}}</ref>
+The '''Christianization of Kyivan Rus'''' was a long and complicated process that took place in several stages.{{sfn|Katchanovski|Kohut|Nesebio|Yurkevich|2013|p=74–75}} In 867, [[Photios I of Constantinople|Patriarch Photius]] of Constantinople told other Christian patriarchs that the [[Rus' people]] were converting enthusiastically, but his efforts seem to have entailed no lasting consequences, since the ''[[Russian Primary Chronicle]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.swarthmore.edu/muslim-russia/rusian-primary-chronicle |title=The Rusian Primary Chronicle |language=en |access-date=2023-11-28 |publisher=Swarthmore}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://philpapers.org/rec/DVOTRP |title=The Russian primary chronicle and the Vlachs of Eastern Europe |language=en |access-date=2023-11-28 |publisher=philpapers.org}}</ref> and other Slavonic sources describe the tenth-century Rus' as still firmly entrenched in [[Slavic paganism]]. The traditional view, as recorded in the ''Russian Primary Chronicle'',<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.swarthmore.edu/muslim-russia/rusian-primary-chronicle |title=The Rusian Primary Chronicle |language=en |access-date=2023-11-28 |publisher=Swarthmore}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://philpapers.org/rec/DVOTRP |title=The Russian primary chronicle and the Vlachs of Eastern Europe |language=en |access-date=2023-11-28 |publisher=philpapers.org}}</ref> is that the definitive Christianization of Kievan Rus' dates happened {{circa}} 988<ref>{{cite web |url=https://human.libretexts.org/Courses/Lumen_Learning/Book%3A_Early_World_Civilizations_(Lumen)/Ch._08_The_Development_of_Russia/09.2%3A_Vladimir_I_and_Christianization |title=Vladimir I and Christianization |language=en |access-date=2023-11-28 |publisher=libretexts}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.advantour.com/russia/history/christianization-of-kievan-rus.htm |title=Christianization of Russia |language=en |access-date=2023-11-28 |publisher=advantour}}</ref> (the year is disputed<ref>Oleg Rapov, ''Russkaya tserkov v IX&ndash;pervoy treti XII veka'' (''The Russian Church from the 9th to the First 3rd of the 12th Century''). Moscow, 1988.</ref>), when [[Vladimir the Great]] was baptized in [[Chersonesus]] (''Korsun'') and proceeded to baptize his family and people in [[Kyiv]]. The latter events are traditionally referred to as '''baptism of Rus' ''' ({{lang-ru|Крещение Руси}}; {{lang-uk|Хрещення Русі}}; {{lang-be|Вадохрышча Русі}}) in Russian, Ukrainian and Belarusian literature.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.belapc.org/litaratura/apanas-martas-belarus-v-istoriceskoj-cerkovnoj-i-gosudarstvennoj-zizni/cast-vtoraa-cerkovnaa---glava-i-hristianstvo-v-belarusi |title=ЧАСТЬ ВТОРАЯ, ЦЕРКОВНАЯ - ГЛАВА I. ХРИСТИАНСТВО В БЕЛАРУСИ |language=ru |access-date=2023-11-28 |publisher=belapc}}</ref>

 == Antiquity ==
-Although sometimes solely attributed to Vladimir/Volodymyr, the Christianization of Kievan Rus' was a long and complicated process that began before the state's formation.{{sfn|Katchanovski|Kohut|Nesebio|Yurkevich|2013|p=74}} As early as the 1st century CE, [[Greek colonisation|Greeks in the Black Sea Colonies]] converted to Christianity, although most of these lands never became part of Kievan Rus'.{{sfn|Katchanovski|Kohut|Nesebio|Yurkevich|2013|p=74}} The ''[[Primary Chronicle]]'' records the legend of [[Andrew the Apostle]]'s mission to these coastal settlements, as well as blessing the site of present-day Kiev.{{sfn|Katchanovski|Kohut|Nesebio|Yurkevich|2013|p=74}} Andrew supposedly visited [[Chersonesus Taurica]] in [[Crimea]], where he converted several thousand men to the new faith, and on his way north along the Dnieper reached the future locations of Kiev.{{according to whom|date=October 2022}} The legendary account in the ''Primary Chronicle'' tells that Andrew was amused by the Slavic customs of washing in a hot steam bath, [[banya (sauna)|banya]], on his way.{{according to whom|date=October 2022}} The [[Goths]] migrated to through the region in the 3rd century, adopting [[Arian Christianity]] in the 4th century, leaving behind 4th- and 5th-century churches excavated in Crimea (which was outside of Kievan control, except for [[Tmutarakan]]), although the [[Huns|Hunnic]] invasion of the 370s halted Christianisation for several centuries.{{sfn|Katchanovski|Kohut|Nesebio|Yurkevich|2013|p=74}}
+Although sometimes solely attributed to Vladimir/Volodymyr, the Christianization of Kyivan Rus' was a long and complicated process that began before the state's formation.{{sfn|Katchanovski|Kohut|Nesebio|Yurkevich|2013|p=74}} As early as the 1st century CE, [[Greek colonisation|Greeks in the Black Sea Colonies]] converted to Christianity, although most of these lands never became part of Kyivan Rus'.{{sfn|Katchanovski|Kohut|Nesebio|Yurkevich|2013|p=74}} The ''[[Primary Chronicle]]'' records the legend of [[Andrew the Apostle]]'s mission to these coastal settlements, as well as blessing the site of present-day Kyiv.{{sfn|Katchanovski|Kohut|Nesebio|Yurkevich|2013|p=74}} Andrew supposedly visited [[Chersonesus Taurica]] in [[Crimea]], where he converted several thousand men to the new faith, and on his way north along the Dnipro reached the future locations of Kyiv.{{according to whom|date=October 2022}} The legendary account in the ''Primary Chronicle'' tells that Andrew was amused by the Slavic customs of washing in a hot steam bath, [[banya (sauna)|banya]], on his way.{{according to whom|date=October 2022}} The [[Goths]] migrated to through the region in the 3rd century, adopting [[Arian Christianity]] in the 4th century, leaving behind 4th- and 5th-century churches excavated in Crimea (which was outside of Kyivan control, except for [[Tmutarakan]]), although the [[Huns|Hunnic]] invasion of the 370s halted Christianisation for several centuries.{{sfn|Katchanovski|Kohut|Nesebio|Yurkevich|2013|p=74}}

 == Ninth century ==
-Some of the earliest Kievan princes and princesses such as [[Askold and Dir]] and [[Olga of Kiev]] reportedly converted to Christianity, but [[Oleg the Wise]], [[Igor of Kiev]] and [[Sviatoslav I]] remained pagans.{{sfn|Katchanovski|Kohut|Nesebio|Yurkevich|2013|p=74–75}} According to some sources and historians, there was an attempt in the 9th century to Christianise Kievan Rus'. The most authoritative source for this purported first conversion attempt is an [[encyclical]] letter of [[Photios I of Constantinople|Patriarch Photius]] of [[Constantinople]], datable to early 867. Referencing the [[Rus'-Byzantine War (860)|Rus'-Byzantine War of 860]], Photius informs the Oriental [[patriarchate|patriarchs]] and bishops that, after the [[First Bulgarian Empire|Bulgarians]] [[Christianization of Bulgaria|turned to Christ]] in 864,<ref>History of the Bulgarians from Antiquity to the 16th Century by Georgi Bakalov (2003) {{ISBN|954-528-289-4}}</ref> the Rus' followed suit so zealously that he found it prudent to send to their land a [[bishop]].<ref>Photii Patriarchae Constantinopolitani Epistulae et Amphilochia. Ed. B. Laourdas, L.G. Westerinck. T.1. Leipzig, 1983. P. 49.</ref>
+Some of the earliest Kyivan princes and princesses such as [[Askold and Dir]] and [[Olga of Kyiv]] reportedly converted to Christianity, but [[Oleg the Wise]], [[Igor of Kyiv]] and [[Sviatoslav I]] remained pagans.{{sfn|Katchanovski|Kohut|Nesebio|Yurkevich|2013|p=74–75}} According to some sources and historians, there was an attempt in the 9th century to Christianise Kyivan Rus'. The most authoritative source for this purported first conversion attempt is an [[encyclical]] letter of [[Photios I of Constantinople|Patriarch Photius]] of [[Constantinople]], datable to early 867. Referencing the [[Rus'-Byzantine War (860)|Rus'-Byzantine War of 860]], Photius informs the Oriental [[patriarchate|patriarchs]] and bishops that, after the [[First Bulgarian Empire|Bulgarians]] [[Christianization of Bulgaria|turned to Christ]] in 864,<ref>History of the Bulgarians from Antiquity to the 16th Century by Georgi Bakalov (2003) {{ISBN|954-528-289-4}}</ref> the Rus' followed suit so zealously that he found it prudent to send to their land a [[bishop]].<ref>Photii Patriarchae Constantinopolitani Epistulae et Amphilochia. Ed. B. Laourdas, L.G. Westerinck. T.1. Leipzig, 1983. P. 49.</ref>
 [[File:58-manasses-chronicle.jpg|thumb|Baptism of the first Rus, illustrated in the 14th century [[Constantine Manasses|Manasses Chronicle]].]]
 Byzantine historians, starting with the continuation of [[Theophanes the Confessor]], assumed that the Rus' [[Rus'-Byzantine War (860)|raid against Constantinople in 860]] was a Byzantine success and attributed the presumed victory to [[the Intercession]] of the [[Theotokos]]. This conviction dictated the following interpretation: awed by the miracles they witnessed under the walls of the imperial capital and grief-stricken at the disaster that befell them, the Rus' sent envoys to Photius and asked him to send a bishop to their land.<ref>Theophanes Continuatus, Ioannes Cameniata, Symeon Magister, Georgius Monachus. Ed. I. Becker. Bonnae, 1838 (CSHB), p. 196.</ref>

