 [[File:Lebedev baptism.jpg|350px|thumb|''The Baptism of Rus{{'}}'' ([[Klavdiy Lebedev]] {{circa}} 1900)]]

-The '''Christianization of Kievan Rus'''' was a long and complicated process that took place in several stages.{{sfn|Katchanovski|Kohut|Nesebio|Yurkevich|2013|p=74–75}} In 867, [[Photios I of Constantinople|Patriarch Photius]] of Constantinople told other Christian patriarchs that the [[Rus' people]] were converting enthusiastically, but his efforts seem to have entailed no lasting consequences, since the ''[[Russian Primary Chronicle]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.swarthmore.edu/muslim-russia/rusian-primary-chronicle |title=The Rusian Primary Chronicle |language=en |access-date=2023-11-28 |publisher=Swarthmore}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://philpapers.org/rec/DVOTRP |title=The Russian primary chronicle and the Vlachs of Eastern Europe |language=en |access-date=2023-11-28 |publisher=philpapers.org}}</ref> and other Slavonic sources describe the tenth-century Rus' as still firmly entrenched in [[Slavic paganism]]. The traditional view, as recorded in the ''Russian Primary Chronicle'',<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.swarthmore.edu/muslim-russia/rusian-primary-chronicle |title=The Rusian Primary Chronicle |language=en |access-date=2023-11-28 |publisher=Swarthmore}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://philpapers.org/rec/DVOTRP |title=The Russian primary chronicle and the Vlachs of Eastern Europe |language=en |access-date=2023-11-28 |publisher=philpapers.org}}</ref> is that the definitive Christianization of Kievan Rus' dates happened {{circa}} 988<ref>{{cite web |url=https://human.libretexts.org/Courses/Lumen_Learning/Book%3A_Early_World_Civilizations_(Lumen)/Ch._08_The_Development_of_Russia/09.2%3A_Vladimir_I_and_Christianization |title=Vladimir I and Christianization |language=en |access-date=2023-11-28 |publisher=libretexts}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.advantour.com/russia/history/christianization-of-kievan-rus.htm |title=Christianization of Russia |language=en |access-date=2023-11-28 |publisher=advantour}}</ref> (the year is disputed<ref>Oleg Rapov, ''Russkaya tserkov v IX&ndash;pervoy treti XII veka'' (''The Russian Church from the 9th to the First 3rd of the 12th Century''). Moscow, 1988.</ref>), when [[Vladimir the Great]] was baptized in [[Chersonesus]] (''Korsun'') and proceeded to baptize his family and people in [[Kiev]]. The latter events are traditionally referred to as '''baptism of Rus' ''' ({{lang-ru|Крещение Руси}}; {{lang-uk|Хрещення Русі}}; {{lang-be|Вадохрышча Русі}}) in Russian, Ukrainian and Belarusian literature.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.belapc.org/litaratura/apanas-martas-belarus-v-istoriceskoj-cerkovnoj-i-gosudarstvennoj-zizni/cast-vtoraa-cerkovnaa---glava-i-hristianstvo-v-belarusi |title=ЧАСТЬ ВТОРАЯ, ЦЕРКОВНАЯ - ГЛАВА I. ХРИСТИАНСТВО В БЕЛАРУСИ |language=ru |access-date=2023-11-28 |publisher=belapc}}</ref>
+The '''Christianization of Kievan Rus'''' was a long and complicated process that took place in several stages.{{sfn|Katchanovski|Kohut|Nesebio|Yurkevich|2013|p=74–75}} In 867, [[Photios I of Constantinople|Patriarch Photius]] of Constantinople told other Christian patriarchs that the [[Rus' people]] were converting enthusiastically, but his efforts seem to have entailed no lasting consequences, since the ''[[Russian Primary Chronicle]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.swarthmore.edu/muslim-russia/rusian-primary-chronicle |title=The Rusian Primary Chronicle |date=8 July 2014 |language=en |access-date=2023-11-28 |publisher=Swarthmore}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |url=https://philpapers.org/rec/DVOTRP |title=The Russian primary chronicle and the Vlachs of Eastern Europe |journal=Byzantion |date=1979 |volume=49 |pages=175–187 |language=en |access-date=2023-11-28 |publisher=philpapers.org |last1=Dvoichenko-Markov |first1=Demetrius de }}</ref> and other Slavonic sources describe the tenth-century Rus' as still firmly entrenched in [[Slavic paganism]]. The traditional view, as recorded in the ''Russian Primary Chronicle'',<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.swarthmore.edu/muslim-russia/rusian-primary-chronicle |title=The Rusian Primary Chronicle |date=8 July 2014 |language=en |access-date=2023-11-28 |publisher=Swarthmore}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |url=https://philpapers.org/rec/DVOTRP |title=The Russian primary chronicle and the Vlachs of Eastern Europe |journal=Byzantion |date=1979 |volume=49 |pages=175–187 |language=en |access-date=2023-11-28 |publisher=philpapers.org |last1=Dvoichenko-Markov |first1=Demetrius de }}</ref> is that the definitive Christianization of Kievan Rus' dates happened {{circa}} 988<ref>{{cite web |url=https://human.libretexts.org/Courses/Lumen_Learning/Book%3A_Early_World_Civilizations_(Lumen)/Ch._08_The_Development_of_Russia/09.2%3A_Vladimir_I_and_Christianization |title=Vladimir I and Christianization |date=27 September 2020 |language=en |access-date=2023-11-28 |publisher=libretexts}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.advantour.com/russia/history/christianization-of-kievan-rus.htm |title=Christianization of Russia |language=en |access-date=2023-11-28 |publisher=advantour}}</ref> (the year is disputed<ref>Oleg Rapov, ''Russkaya tserkov v IX&ndash;pervoy treti XII veka'' (''The Russian Church from the 9th to the First 3rd of the 12th Century''). Moscow, 1988.</ref>), when [[Vladimir the Great]] was baptized in [[Chersonesus]] (''Korsun'') and proceeded to baptize his family and people in [[Kiev]]. The latter events are traditionally referred to as '''baptism of Rus' ''' ({{lang-ru|Крещение Руси}}; {{lang-uk|Хрещення Русі}}; {{lang-be|Вадохрышча Русі}}) in Russian, Ukrainian and Belarusian literature.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.belapc.org/litaratura/apanas-martas-belarus-v-istoriceskoj-cerkovnoj-i-gosudarstvennoj-zizni/cast-vtoraa-cerkovnaa---glava-i-hristianstvo-v-belarusi |title=ЧАСТЬ ВТОРАЯ, ЦЕРКОВНАЯ - ГЛАВА I. ХРИСТИАНСТВО В БЕЛАРУСИ |language=ru |access-date=2023-11-28 |publisher=belapc}}</ref>

 == Antiquity ==
 Although sometimes solely attributed to Vladimir/Volodymyr, the Christianization of Kievan Rus' was a long and complicated process that began before the state's formation.{{sfn|Katchanovski|Kohut|Nesebio|Yurkevich|2013|p=74}} As early as the 1st century CE, [[Greek colonisation|Greeks in the Black Sea Colonies]] converted to Christianity, although most of these lands never became part of Kievan Rus'.{{sfn|Katchanovski|Kohut|Nesebio|Yurkevich|2013|p=74}} The ''[[Primary Chronicle]]'' records the legend of [[Andrew the Apostle]]'s mission to these coastal settlements, as well as blessing the site of present-day Kiev.{{sfn|Katchanovski|Kohut|Nesebio|Yurkevich|2013|p=74}} Andrew supposedly visited [[Chersonesus Taurica]] in [[Crimea]], where he converted several thousand men to the new faith, and on his way north along the Dnipro reached the future locations of Kiev.{{according to whom|date=October 2022}} The legendary account in the ''Primary Chronicle'' tells that Andrew was amused by the Slavic customs of washing in a hot steam bath, [[banya (sauna)|banya]], on his way.{{according to whom|date=October 2022}} The [[Goths]] migrated to through the region in the 3rd century, adopting [[Arian Christianity]] in the 4th century, leaving behind 4th- and 5th-century churches excavated in Crimea (which was outside of Kievan control, except for [[Tmutarakan]]), although the [[Huns|Hunnic]] invasion of the 370s halted Christianisation for several centuries.{{sfn|Katchanovski|Kohut|Nesebio|Yurkevich|2013|p=74}}
