+
+For one, the chronicle says explicitly ''sub anno'' 6491 (983): 'the Apostles were not by body here';{{efn|'Аще бо и тѣлъмь апостоли суть не были' (PVL 83.20–21).{{sfn|Ostrowski|Birnbaum|2014|loc=83.20–21}}}} 'the apostles did not teach here; and also the prophets did not prophecy here'{{efn|'сьде бо не суть учили апостоли, ни пророци прорекли.' (PVL 83.15–16).{{sfn|Ostrowski|Birnbaum|2014|loc=83.15–16}}}}.{{sfn|Santos Marinas|2011|p=328}} Secondly, the legend of Andrew travelling through Scythia dates from the 3rd or 4th century, and it was not until the 9th century that the monk Epiphanius wrote a ''vita'' in Greek about Andrew that mentions the cities of Sinope and Kherson for the first time.{{sfn|Santos Marinas|2011|p=328}} Moreover, the external evidence suggests nobody was aware of the legend of Andrew blessing the future site of Kyiv until the late 11th century, and the internal evidence suggests that the trip to the would-be Novgorod Slavs was the first [[Interpolation (manuscripts)|interpolation]] – as Andrew tells people about it in Rome, but says nothing about erecting a cross and blessing the future site of Kyiv.{{sfn|Santos Marinas|2011|p=328}} Therefore, the latter would have been a secondary interpolation that was only formulated later in order to claim an apostolic origin for Kyiv.{{sfn|Santos Marinas|2011|pp=328–329}}

 == Ninth century ==
 Some of the earliest Kievan princes and princesses such as [[Askold and Dir]] and [[Olga of Kiev]] reportedly converted to Christianity, but [[Oleg the Wise]], [[Igor of Kiev]] and [[Sviatoslav I]] remained pagans.{{sfn|Katchanovski|Kohut|Nesebio|Yurkevich|2013|p=74–75}} According to some sources and historians, there was an attempt in the 9th century to Christianise Kievan Rus'. The most authoritative source for this purported first conversion attempt is an [[encyclical]] letter of [[Photios I of Constantinople|Patriarch Photius]] of [[Constantinople]], datable to early 867. Referencing the [[Rus'-Byzantine War (860)|Rus'-Byzantine War of 860]], Photius informs the Oriental [[patriarchate|patriarchs]] and bishops that, after the [[First Bulgarian Empire|Bulgarians]] [[Christianization of Bulgaria|turned to Christ]] in 864,<ref>History of the Bulgarians from Antiquity to the 16th Century by Georgi Bakalov (2003) {{ISBN|954-528-289-4}}</ref> the Rus' followed suit so zealously that he found it prudent to send to their land a [[bishop]].<ref>Photii Patriarchae Constantinopolitani Epistulae et Amphilochia. Ed. B. Laourdas, L.G. Westerinck. T.1. Leipzig, 1983. P. 49.</ref>

