-The '''Christianization of Kievan Rus'''' was a long and complicated process that took place in several stages.{{sfn|Katchanovski|Kohut|Nesebio|Yurkevich|2013|p=74–75}} In 867, [[Photios I of Constantinople|Patriarch Photius]] of Constantinople told other Christian patriarchs that the [[Rus' people]] were converting enthusiastically, but his efforts seem to have entailed no lasting consequences, since the ''[[Russian Primary Chronicle]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.swarthmore.edu/muslim-russia/rusian-primary-chronicle |title=The Rusian Primary Chronicle |date=8 July 2014 |language=en |access-date=2023-11-28 |publisher=Swarthmore}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |url=https://philpapers.org/rec/DVOTRP |title=The Russian primary chronicle and the Vlachs of Eastern Europe |journal=Byzantion |date=1979 |volume=49 |pages=175–187 |language=en |access-date=2023-11-28 |publisher=philpapers.org |last1=Dvoichenko-Markov |first1=Demetrius de }}</ref> and other Slavonic sources describe the tenth-century Rus' as still firmly entrenched in [[Slavic paganism]]. The traditional view, as recorded in the ''Russian Primary Chronicle'',<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.swarthmore.edu/muslim-russia/rusian-primary-chronicle |title=The Rusian Primary Chronicle |date=8 July 2014 |language=en |access-date=2023-11-28 |publisher=Swarthmore}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |url=https://philpapers.org/rec/DVOTRP |title=The Russian primary chronicle and the Vlachs of Eastern Europe |journal=Byzantion |date=1979 |volume=49 |pages=175–187 |language=en |access-date=2023-11-28 |publisher=philpapers.org |last1=Dvoichenko-Markov |first1=Demetrius de }}</ref> is that the definitive Christianization of Kievan Rus' dates happened {{circa}} 988<ref>{{cite web |url=https://human.libretexts.org/Courses/Lumen_Learning/Book%3A_Early_World_Civilizations_(Lumen)/Ch._08_The_Development_of_Russia/09.2%3A_Vladimir_I_and_Christianization |title=Vladimir I and Christianization |date=27 September 2020 |language=en |access-date=2023-11-28 |publisher=libretexts}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.advantour.com/russia/history/christianization-of-kievan-rus.htm |title=Christianization of Russia |language=en |access-date=2023-11-28 |publisher=advantour}}</ref> (the year is disputed<ref>Oleg Rapov, ''Russkaya tserkov v IX&ndash;pervoy treti XII veka'' (''The Russian Church from the 9th to the First 3rd of the 12th Century''). Moscow, 1988.</ref>), when [[Vladimir the Great]] was baptized in [[Chersonesus]] (''Korsun'') and proceeded to baptize his family and people in [[Kiev]]. The latter events are traditionally referred to as '''baptism of Rus' ''' ({{lang-ru|Крещение Руси}}; {{lang-uk|Хрещення Русі}}; {{lang-be|Вадохрышча Русі}}) in Russian, Ukrainian and Belarusian literature.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.belapc.org/litaratura/apanas-martas-belarus-v-istoriceskoj-cerkovnoj-i-gosudarstvennoj-zizni/cast-vtoraa-cerkovnaa---glava-i-hristianstvo-v-belarusi |title=ЧАСТЬ ВТОРАЯ, ЦЕРКОВНАЯ - ГЛАВА I. ХРИСТИАНСТВО В БЕЛАРУСИ |language=ru |access-date=2023-11-28 |publisher=belapc}}</ref>
+The '''Christianization of Kyivan Rus'''' was a long and complicated process that took place in several stages.{{sfn|Katchanovski|Kohut|Nesebio|Yurkevich|2013|p=74–75}} In 867, [[Photios I of Constantinople|Patriarch Photius]] of Constantinople told other Christian patriarchs that the [[Rus' people]] were converting enthusiastically, but his efforts seem to have entailed no lasting consequences, since the ''[[Russian Primary Chronicle]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.swarthmore.edu/muslim-russia/rusian-primary-chronicle |title=The Rusian Primary Chronicle |date=8 July 2014 |language=en |access-date=2023-11-28 |publisher=Swarthmore}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |url=https://philpapers.org/rec/DVOTRP |title=The Russian primary chronicle and the Vlachs of Eastern Europe |journal=Byzantion |date=1979 |volume=49 |pages=175–187 |language=en |access-date=2023-11-28 |publisher=philpapers.org |last1=Dvoichenko-Markov |first1=Demetrius de }}</ref> and other Slavonic sources describe the tenth-century Rus' as still firmly entrenched in [[Slavic paganism]]. The traditional view, as recorded in the ''Russian Primary Chronicle'',<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.swarthmore.edu/muslim-russia/rusian-primary-chronicle |title=The Rusian Primary Chronicle |date=8 July 2014 |language=en |access-date=2023-11-28 |publisher=Swarthmore}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |url=https://philpapers.org/rec/DVOTRP |title=The Russian primary chronicle and the Vlachs of Eastern Europe |journal=Byzantion |date=1979 |volume=49 |pages=175–187 |language=en |access-date=2023-11-28 |publisher=philpapers.org |last1=Dvoichenko-Markov |first1=Demetrius de }}</ref> is that the definitive Christianization of Kyivan Rus' dates happened {{circa}} 988<ref>{{cite web |url=https://human.libretexts.org/Courses/Lumen_Learning/Book%3A_Early_World_Civilizations_(Lumen)/Ch._08_The_Development_of_Russia/09.2%3A_Vladimir_I_and_Christianization |title=Vladimir I and Christianization |date=27 September 2020 |language=en |access-date=2023-11-28 |publisher=libretexts}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.advantour.com/russia/history/christianization-of-kievan-rus.htm |title=Christianization of Russia |language=en |access-date=2023-11-28 |publisher=advantour}}</ref> (the year is disputed<ref>Oleg Rapov, ''Russkaya tserkov v IX&ndash;pervoy treti XII veka'' (''The Russian Church from the 9th to the First 3rd of the 12th Century''). Moscow, 1988.</ref>), when [[Volodymyr the Great]] was baptized in [[Chersonesus]] (''Korsun'') and proceeded to baptize his family and people in [[Kyiv]]. The latter events are traditionally referred to as '''baptism of Rus' ''' ({{lang-ru|Крещение Руси}}; {{lang-uk|Хрещення Русі}}; {{lang-be|Вадохрышча Русі}}) in Ukrainian and Belarusian literature.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.belapc.org/litaratura/apanas-martas-belarus-v-istoriceskoj-cerkovnoj-i-gosudarstvennoj-zizni/cast-vtoraa-cerkovnaa---glava-i-hristianstvo-v-belarusi |title=ЧАСТЬ ВТОРАЯ, ЦЕРКОВНАЯ - ГЛАВА I. ХРИСТИАНСТВО В БЕЛАРУСИ |language=ru |access-date=2023-11-28 |publisher=belapc}}</ref>

 == Antiquity ==
 === Early presence ===
-Although sometimes solely attributed to Vladimir/Volodymyr, the Christianization of Kievan Rus' was a long and complicated process that began before the state's formation.{{sfn|Katchanovski|Kohut|Nesebio|Yurkevich|2013|p=74}} As early as the 1st century CE, [[Greek colonisation|Greeks in the Black Sea Colonies]] converted to Christianity, although most of these lands never became part of Kievan Rus'.{{sfn|Katchanovski|Kohut|Nesebio|Yurkevich|2013|p=74}} 
