-Although sometimes solely attributed to Vladimir/Volodymyr, the Christianization of Kievan Rus' was a long and complicated process that began before the state's formation.{{sfn|Katchanovski|Kohut|Nesebio|Yurkevich|2013|p=74}} As early as the 1st century CE, [[Greek colonisation|Greeks in the Black Sea Colonies]] converted to Christianity, although most of these lands never became part of Kievan Rus'.{{sfn|Katchanovski|Kohut|Nesebio|Yurkevich|2013|p=74}} 
+Although sometimes solely attributed to Vladimir/Volodymyr, the Christianization of Kievan Rus' was a long and complicated process that began before the state's formation.{{sfn|Katchanovski|Kohut|Nesebio|Yurkevich|2013|p=74}} As early as the 1st century AD, [[Greek colonisation|Greeks in the Black Sea Colonies]] converted to Christianity, although most of these lands never became part of Kievan Rus'.{{sfn|Katchanovski|Kohut|Nesebio|Yurkevich|2013|p=74}} 

 The [[Goths]] migrated to through the region in the 3rd century, adopting [[Arian Christianity]] in the 4th century, leaving behind 4th- and 5th-century churches excavated in Crimea (which was outside of Kievan control, except for [[Tmutarakan]]), although the [[Huns|Hunnic]] invasion of the 370s halted Christianisation for several centuries.{{sfn|Katchanovski|Kohut|Nesebio|Yurkevich|2013|p=74}}

